\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
This paper discusses the problem of data Independencies that is when there are changes in internal or external aspects of representation of data there should be minimal or no effect to users at the terminal end or in the applications accessing this data, and also data inconsistencies.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
The advantages of relational model are it deals with derivability, redundancy, and consistency of relations.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
The data can be stored different forms of orders of the records. Many applications fail to differentiate between the data storage ordering and data presentation ordering as a result applications can fail if the data stored ordering has to be changed.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
Indexing data is with both pros and cons as it improves performance while querying and performing updates on data but they deteriorate the performance while inserting and deleting data and also is a redundant overhead. To perform well in changing patterns environment the indices need to be created and destroyed. Different applications provide different indexing properties.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
The access paths for data are represented in tree-structures or networking model, but many applications fail if any of underlying model is\line altered. To deal this problem an impractical solution suggested was to not to decide an access path to be obsolete till all the application programs use the path.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
The relational model is well explained with its properties such as: Each row is distinct, representing n-tuple in an n-ary relation \u8216\'91R\u8217\'92 with no particular order and each column has distinct order and well are defined with a label. Ordering of columns is needed as the order determines the relation in some tables, if the domain names are identical and to deal with time-varying relations. But if the relation is of higher order it is better to have unique domain names and the relations as domain-unordered.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
A domain that is unique over all the tuples in a relation is called the primary key of the relation. The main attribute of primary key is to be non-redundant and it might be a simple domain or a combination. If there are more than one simple domain with such properties one among them can be selected as the primary key of the relation.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
The requirement of Primary key is for cross-reference of elements in same relation or elements of other relation. In the second case to cross-reference elements in other relation the foreign key of a relation should be a primary key for another relation.\line The process of eliminating non-simple domains is called normalization. Identifying the primary key and inserting it over other relations as foreign key and eliminating the redundant/complex domains across all the relations and recursively performing this procedure over all the relations until all the relations has simple domains will normalize a data set.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
The primary conditions for an unnormalized relation to be able to normalize are: Must have non-simple domains, which are collection of trees, and the primary key should have a simple component domain. Not only storage and representation of data but also the communication of bulk data is simplified through Normalization.\line The normal form of data can be represented through first ordered predicate calculus. Which would simplify the ability to access the data form large data bank and communication through different programming languages. The required arithmetic functions can be defined in the programming language and invoked in relation.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
A network view uses more names for data elements than required, as the names are also associated with their paths rather than their relations. A certain stored relation can be exploited with using the combinations of its arguments with knowns and unknowns and this is called symmetric exploitation. For an n-ary relation to support symmetric exploitation it needs n factorial paths to be named and controlled. To express an n-ary relation using only (nested) binary representation it needs 2n-1 names instead of n+1 names using n-ary notation.\line The two collections of relations are named set and expressible set where \u8216\'91named set\u8217\'92 is a subset of \u8216\'91expressible set\u8217\'92. A named set is a collection of relations, which can be identified by simple name. A relation can be a member of a named set if declared by an authorized user. An expressible set is collection of relations designated by expressions in data language. These are constructed from simple names of relations in named set.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
To determine the class of stored representation to be supported is one of the major problems of the designer. In a stored representation data should allow to translate user request to corresponding relational model.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
All usual set operations can be applicable on relations and result may not be a relation. Permutation, Projection, Join, Composition, and Restriction are some operations specific for relations.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
Permutation: when a permutation (interchanging of columns) is applied to the columns of and n-ary relation it results in a relation known as permutation of a given relation. There is n! Possible results.\line Projection: certain selected rows in a relation are duplicated as a new relation leaving unselected rows.\line Join: Two relations, which can be joined without loss of information to form new relation. An element, which gives plurality to a join, is called \u8216\'91point of ambiguity\u8217\'92.\line Composition: composition is a projection of a join thus only joinable relations are composable and two relations need not have n composition even though there exists n joins among them.\line Restriction: restriction is a subset of a relation, which eventually is a relation. Restriction is defined only if equality is applicable among the elements of the relations.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
Two types of possible redundancies are in named set of relations and stored set of representations. If a collection of operations (\u952\'3f) in a certain order on relation R results in a particular relation S for all time then Relation R is \u952\'3f derivable from set S.\line If a relation exists in a set of relations that has the projection, which can be derived from other projections of relations in the set, then the set is known as strong redundant. The existence of strong redundancy is for user convenience to cope with the traffic. This may result in existence of both named and stored representations. But if the redundancy in the stored set exists, this will drop the query time and will be a occupying extra storage space and update time.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
If a relation that has projection, which is not directly derivable form, other projections of relations but it from the projection of some join of other projections in the set it is known as weak redundancy. The weak redundancy exists in both stored set and named set of representations and exists due to logical needs of community users.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sl288\slmult1\sb0\sa140\sl364\slmult0\widctlpar\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa0{\scaps0\caps0\cf1\expnd0\expndtw0\i0\b0\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs18\loch\f5
